{{for|the New Zealand artist|Andrew Drummond (artist)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} [[File:AndrewDrummond2.jpg|thumbnail|right|Andrew Drummond]] '''Andrew Drummond''' is a Scottish [[translation|translator]] and [[novelist]]. He was born in [[Edinburgh]] and studied at the [[University of Aberdeen]] and the [[University of London]]. He writes part-time, working full-time as a [[software engineer]].
He is the [[author]] of four books, the historical novel ''An Abridged History of the Construction of a Railway Line Between Ullapool and Lochinver''<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Parker |title=Fiction: An Abridged History by Andrew Drummond; The Blackpool Highflyer by Andrew Martin |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/books/article239245.ece |work=The Sunday Times |date=26 September 2004 |subscription=yes}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last1=Wright |first1=Peter |title=Ribbon of Wildness: Discovering the Watershed of Scotland |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=31boMSQ7X6cC&pg=PA194&lpg=PA194&dq=%22Andrew+Drummond%22+%22An+Abridged+History%22&source=bl&ots=WFC48x6ieS&sig=Tr0uJmwEEqb8h6Ew_VV_iMWCLps&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EmZlVKW-PMjpaNO_gbAM&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=%22Andrew%20Drummond%22%20%22An%20Abridged%20History%22&f=false |page=194 |year=2010|isbn=978-1-906817-45-9 }}</ref> (2004), ''A Hand-book of [[Volapük]]'' (2006)<ref>{{cite news|author=Bill Greenwell |title= Volapük, by Andrew Drummond: Laughter and lunacy in a vanishing language |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/volapuumlk-by-andrew-drummond-414155.html |work=The Independent |date=1 September 2006 |accessdate=2014-11-13 }}</ref> set in 1890s Scotland, ''Elephantina'' (2008), and ''Novgorod the Great'' (2010). He has also written several short stories and some nonfiction translations from German. More recently, he has written a biography of the 18th century adventurer [[Maurice Benyovszky]], entitled ''The Intriguing Life and Ignominious Death of Maurice Benyovszky'' (2017).
